  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Seinoli: Lesotho Dams and Environmental Justice Project</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Phase 1 of the Lesotho Highlands Water Project (LHWP), which supplies water to South Africa, forcibly displaced more than 50,000 poor subsistence farmers living in the dam areas. A compensation and resettlement package was agreed with these communities. But in reality, there have been serious delays and what has actually been offered has been inadequate. The result is that thousands of families have been made destitute.  These communities, used to farming and keeping livestock, and with little experience of a cash economy, have been resettled within slum settlements &#x2013; many of which are now blighted by toxic waste discharge from factories.   This project will build on a recent record of success in conducting corruption trials in Lesotho related to LHWP, and aims to ensure that forcibly displaced families and communities get better, and timely, compensation. The project will also tackle the government and businesses on improving toxic pollution control.  The project will work with and build the capacity of existing community co-operative societies of the displaced highlanders, and train them in awareness of their rights, legal processes, communication, and negotiation skills. A new organisation formed of forcibly removed highlanders will be supported to become a stronger voice of the people. Local lawyers will be trained in public interest law. As a result of this multi-pronged approach, communities will experience improvements in their lives and they will be more able to stand up for their rights, and expertise in public-interest law, not previously present in Lesotho, will have been created to defend people&apos;s rights in the future.</narrative>
  </description>
